contact www.OpenSubtitles.org today

04:22.174 --> 04:24.682
<i>[FOOTSTEPS]</i>

04:24.707 --> 04:26.100
Who are you?

04:26.855 --> 04:28.652
Who are you?

04:29.402 --> 04:31.202
The name's Allie.

04:31.227 --> 04:33.000
And I'm lookin' for my Uncle Nathan.

04:33.176 --> 04:34.631
"Uncle" Nathan.

04:34.749 --> 04:36.480
Oh, well he's out right now.

04:36.505 --> 04:37.930
He'll probably be back soon.

04:37.955 --> 04:39.655
You must be Bill, right?

04:39.845 --> 04:41.100
Bill the Sheriff?

04:41.125 --> 04:42.583
Well, you can call me Sir.

04:42.892 --> 04:44.468
You're funny.

04:44.493 --> 04:47.143
My uncle says you have
been sorta nice to him.

04:47.282 --> 04:48.658
"Sorta nice?"

04:48.930 --> 04:51.452
Allie! Hey.

04:52.546 --> 04:54.173
You were supposed to wait for
me at the train station.

04:54.198 --> 04:57.101
The train was early, so I
thought I'd surprise you.

04:57.190 --> 04:58.569
I see you've met my niece.

04:58.594 --> 04:59.627
Yes!

04:59.652 --> 05:00.917
I've had the pleasure.

05:00.942 --> 05:03.314
Well, come on, let's
get you settled in.

05:10.342 --> 05:11.608
Really, Uncle Nathan?

05:11.633 --> 05:13.963
On my first day here?

05:13.988 --> 05:15.158
You've heard the saying,

05:15.183 --> 05:16.420
"there's no time like the present."

05:16.445 --> 05:18.436
Or, how about "don't
go to school today,

05:18.461 --> 05:20.721
"if we can wait til tomorrow."

05:21.025 --> 05:22.802
Okay, well, first of
all, you made that up,

05:22.827 --> 05:25.161
and second, I don't want
you falling behind.

05:25.196 --> 05:27.391
But the school day's already started...

05:27.416 --> 05:29.087
That's great; now you can
go make a grand entrance.

05:29.112 --> 05:29.955
Fine.

05:29.980 --> 05:31.799
Just let me go in by myself.

05:32.410 --> 05:35.657
You're just like my sister;
bull-headed and independent.

05:37.271 --> 05:38.287
[SIGHS]

05:38.312 --> 05:39.127
Okay, fine.

05:39.152 --> 05:40.362
You can go in by yourself,
but remember...

05:40.387 --> 05:42.946
"Walk tall, look 'em straight
in the eyes and shake hands."

05:43.357 --> 05:46.370
Now, please: give me this moment.

06:11.819 --> 06:13.166
Good idea...

06:13.524 --> 06:14.590
Good morning, Carson.

06:14.615 --> 06:15.770
Morning, ladies.

06:15.795 --> 06:17.137
Well, where are you headed?

06:17.162 --> 06:20.332
Off to Benson Hills, to pick up
an electro-cardiograph machine.

06:20.357 --> 06:21.738
Oh, and what does that do?

06:21.763 --> 06:23.768
Measures electric activity
in someone's heart.

06:23.793 --> 06:25.260
Oh, that sounds pretty sophisticated.

06:25.285 --> 06:26.239
Yes.

06:26.264 --> 06:27.943
Yeah. It is.

06:29.669 --> 06:30.836
Oh!

06:30.861 --> 06:32.247
Good morning.

06:33.092 --> 06:34.945
Are you going to...

06:34.970 --> 06:36.431
Pick up an...?

06:36.456 --> 06:37.637
Electro-cardiograph machine.

06:37.662 --> 06:38.415
<i>Mmm-hmm.</i>

06:38.440 --> 06:40.061
And supplies.

06:40.086 --> 06:41.331
<i>Medical ones.</i>

06:41.356 --> 06:44.639
Tongue depressors, and
bandages, and such.

06:44.962 --> 06:47.740
I'll be getting those while
Carson gets the machine.

06:47.840 --> 06:49.206
<i>I know the brands.</i>

06:49.231 --> 06:51.640
And besides, two sets of
hands are better than one.

06:51.976 --> 06:53.018
Right?

06:53.043 --> 06:54.208
Yep.

06:55.709 --> 06:57.666
Well, have fun.

06:58.364 --> 06:59.929
Thank you.

07:06.290 --> 07:07.856
Do you think they know?

07:09.251 --> 07:10.285
What?

07:10.310 --> 07:13.679
Did you know that your upper lip
perspires when you tell a lie?

07:13.784 --> 07:14.802
Really?

07:14.827 --> 07:15.510
Yeah.

07:15.543 --> 07:17.438
You're like Pinocchio, but sweaty.

07:17.463 --> 07:18.924
Oh, shush!

07:18.949 --> 07:20.916
[LAUGHS]

07:32.473 --> 07:34.117
Hi boy.

07:34.853 --> 07:37.391
Today is an outstanding
day, the sun is shining.

07:37.416 --> 07:39.904
<i>You want to pick it up.
Go around back or just...</i>

07:42.118 --> 07:43.280
Whoa!

07:43.305 --> 07:44.892
Sorry, Mister.

07:45.446 --> 07:46.844
Are you lost?

07:50.275 --> 07:51.863
<i>I'm never lost.</i>

07:53.788 --> 07:55.613
Are you a fugitive from justice?

07:55.638 --> 07:57.371
No...

07:57.439 --> 07:59.039
So, you're just skipping school, then?

07:59.064 --> 08:00.630
Kids are so boring.

08:00.655 --> 08:03.265
Adults are so much more interesting.

08:03.440 --> 08:06.289
Well, you must be hanging
around different adults, then.

08:07.040 --> 08:10.033
Besides, I'm no good
at making any friends.

08:10.058 --> 08:11.461
Neither was I, when I was your age.

08:11.486 --> 08:12.889
Oh yeah?

08:12.987 --> 08:14.586
I was a bit of a loner.

08:14.789 --> 08:17.212
But, I discovered a sure-fire
way to make friends.

08:17.535 --> 08:18.801
What's that?

08:18.860 --> 08:20.502
To amaze them.

08:21.286 --> 08:22.773
Nice!

08:28.236 --> 08:29.902
Pick a card.

08:33.812 --> 08:35.178
Now, remember it.

08:35.203 --> 08:36.600
Place it back in the deck.

08:39.610 --> 08:41.110
Let's make this interesting.

08:41.135 --> 08:44.114
If I can't guess your card,
I'll give you a dollar.

08:44.139 --> 08:44.953
Okay.

08:44.978 --> 08:47.594
But if I can, you need
to go back to school.

08:47.619 --> 08:49.703
On one condition;

08:50.477 --> 08:51.921
you teach me the card trick!

08:51.946 --> 08:52.849
[LAUGHS]

08:52.874 --> 08:54.572
[CHUCKLES] You can't add
a condition to a bet.

08:54.597 --> 08:56.029
It's not very sporting.

08:56.054 --> 08:57.445
Please?

09:00.303 --> 09:01.870
Fine.

09:01.895 --> 09:03.527
<i>[CARDS SHUFFLING]</i>

09:07.061 --> 09:08.514
Sheriff Bill Avery?

09:08.539 --> 09:09.575
That's me.

09:09.600 --> 09:10.651
Ronald Peterman.

09:10.676 --> 09:12.332
I'm the Governor's Chief of Staff.

09:12.357 --> 09:14.932
I sent a letter notifying
you of my arrival.

09:15.610 --> 09:18.649
Uh, yes, I uh, think I
received it recently.

09:18.674 --> 09:19.968
It was in reference to Cape Fullerton

09:19.993 --> 09:21.782
and Judge Aaron Southwick?

09:22.153 --> 09:23.854
But what would you have me do?

09:23.879 --> 09:25.436
That judge set those gunrunners free;

09:25.461 --> 09:26.621
there was no time for niceties.

09:26.646 --> 09:27.431
Sheriff...

09:27.456 --> 09:28.788
Now, I know it shouldn't
have come to that.

09:28.813 --> 09:30.303
But the governor shouldn't
be appointing people

09:30.328 --> 09:32.601
that can be easily
intimidated like that.

09:32.878 --> 09:34.432
And I don't mean to
speak out of turn here,

09:34.457 --> 09:36.667
but we need judges that
are tough, but fair,

09:36.692 --> 09:37.799
but especially tough.

09:37.824 --> 09:38.494
You mean like you?

09:38.519 --> 09:39.314
Yes!

09:39.339 --> 09:40.338
That's why I'm here.

09:40.363 --> 09:41.158
Excuse me?

09:41.183 --> 09:42.581
Judge Southwick is out.

09:43.001 --> 09:45.115
The governor wants you to replace him.

09:45.477 --> 09:46.576
Me?!

09:46.601 --> 09:48.068
Yes sir.

09:50.607 --> 09:53.174
Well, that's not how I saw
this conversation going.

09:53.199 --> 09:55.001
So, are you interested?

09:58.470 --> 10:02.531
Well, frankly, I've
always felt that judges,

10:02.556 --> 10:04.750
lawyers and politicians
were pretty spineless.

10:04.775 --> 10:06.173
No offence.

10:06.198 --> 10:09.195
Fortunately, tact isn't a
requirement for this job.

10:10.101 --> 10:12.769
[SIGHS]

10:13.343 --> 10:14.819
I need to think about this.

10:14.844 --> 10:16.210
Let me know.

10:16.235 --> 10:17.972
I'll be in touch.

10:23.608 --> 10:25.044
Mrs. Thornton!

10:25.219 --> 10:27.442
Yes, hello, Constable Grant.

10:27.950 --> 10:29.384
So?

10:29.656 --> 10:30.788
How was she?

10:30.813 --> 10:31.878
How was who?

10:31.903 --> 10:33.103
Allie, she's my niece.

10:33.128 --> 10:34.972
She was in your class today.

10:35.384 --> 10:37.509
I'm sorry, Allie?

10:38.699 --> 10:39.865
[SIGHS]

10:39.890 --> 10:41.822
I knew I shoulda walked in with her.

10:42.378 --> 10:43.610
This is your niece?

10:43.635 --> 10:44.570
[SIGHS]

10:44.595 --> 10:45.662
Yes.

10:45.687 --> 10:47.234
She's 10 going on 17.

10:47.259 --> 10:49.694
[SMALL CHUCKLE]

10:49.959 --> 10:51.458
[SIGHS]

10:51.736 --> 10:53.616
I haven't seen her all day.

10:54.018 --> 10:57.787
Constable, would you like my help?

10:57.812 --> 11:00.901
[SIGHS] Yes.

11:01.114 --> 11:02.692
Please.

11:08.036 --> 11:09.238
Anything?

11:09.263 --> 11:10.425
No.

11:10.450 --> 11:11.568
Did you check the livery?

11:11.593 --> 11:13.406
Yes. Twice.

11:13.622 --> 11:14.871
Well, what does she like to do?

11:14.896 --> 11:19.500
Climb trees, ride
horses, collect frogs.

11:20.203 --> 11:21.635
Fish?

11:21.671 --> 11:23.535
Yeah, how'd you know that?

11:27.497 --> 11:29.297
[SIGHS]

11:29.322 --> 11:30.990
Thank you.

11:34.712 --> 11:36.898
Hey, Uncle Nathan.

11:38.419 --> 11:39.586
Look!

11:39.611 --> 11:40.982
We can have these for dinner.

11:41.007 --> 11:42.068
It's nice.

11:42.093 --> 11:43.677
So, tell me, how was school today?

11:43.702 --> 11:45.655
Pfft. Oh, you know.

11:45.680 --> 11:47.718
No, I don't know.

11:47.743 --> 11:49.485
That's why I'm asking.

11:49.667 --> 11:52.050
It was like any old school day.

11:52.111 --> 11:54.559
Take boring, and then multiply by two.

11:55.455 --> 11:57.530
And how did you like Mrs. Thornton?

11:58.661 --> 12:00.247
That's your teacher.

12:00.272 --> 12:01.315
Oh. Pfft.

12:01.340 --> 12:03.563
A bit bossy, smelled like chalk.

12:03.588 --> 12:05.184
<i>Oh.</i>

12:06.220 --> 12:09.068
So, you know that this is her.

12:09.384 --> 12:11.031
Right?

12:12.368 --> 12:13.905
Hi Allie.

12:14.093 --> 12:15.554
See you tomorrow then?

12:16.383 --> 12:17.616
Yes.

12:17.641 --> 12:18.808
Absolutely.

12:18.833 --> 12:20.242
Right?

12:20.547 --> 12:22.319
Yes, Sir.

12:24.449 --> 12:26.152
Thank you for helping me find her.

12:26.177 --> 12:27.876
Mm-hmm.

12:28.243 --> 12:29.448
I'm sorry.

12:29.473 --> 12:31.120
Yeah, so am I.

12:31.647 --> 12:33.924
Allie, always do what you
say you're going to do.

12:34.091 --> 12:37.213
No matter how inconvenient
or not fun it is.

12:38.018 --> 12:39.250
Okay.

12:39.275 --> 12:41.275
Do you understand the
importance of what I said?

12:41.300 --> 12:43.552
I'm sorry, Uncle Nathan.

12:44.737 --> 12:46.437
Okay, well.

12:46.462 --> 12:48.259
Let's go home and cook these up

12:48.284 --> 12:51.402
and hope that they're less
fishy than your story.

12:52.177 --> 12:53.825
Come on, that was pretty funny.

12:53.850 --> 12:55.561
We gotta work on your jokes.

12:55.586 --> 12:56.685
That was funny!

12:56.710 --> 12:58.022
We gotta work on 'em.

12:58.047 --> 12:59.180
Aaah!

13:03.313 --> 13:05.948
I guess I should pick up
those extra supplies.

13:05.983 --> 13:07.892
Yeah, you wouldn't want your
cover story to fall apart.

13:07.917 --> 13:09.484
[CHUCKLES]

13:09.887 --> 13:11.404
You know what would be fun?

13:11.429 --> 13:13.832
Walking arm in arm down the street.

13:13.994 --> 13:14.993
Yes.

13:15.018 --> 13:16.142
Like a real couple.

13:16.167 --> 13:17.867
Without the town's scrutiny.

13:17.892 --> 13:19.430
[LAUGHS]

13:19.455 --> 13:21.890
Perfect.

13:22.182 --> 13:23.514
[BABY COOS]

13:23.707 --> 13:25.601
Hello!

13:25.626 --> 13:27.043
<i>He just woke up from his nap.</i>

13:27.068 --> 13:28.262
He's a heavy sleeper.

13:28.287 --> 13:30.615
Oh, when he finally decides to sleep.

13:30.640 --> 13:33.941
Lately, it seems like he
thinks 2:00AM is playtime,

13:33.977 --> 13:35.642
which it isn't.

13:37.247 --> 13:38.709
Maybe you should try and take a nap.

13:38.734 --> 13:40.234
Oh, I wish I could.

13:40.269 --> 13:43.085
I'm already three days
behind grading these papers.

13:43.110 --> 13:44.509
[KNOCKS]

13:44.534 --> 13:46.391
Dinner will be ready by 7:00.

13:46.416 --> 13:48.326
[SIGHS DISAPPOINTEDLY]

13:48.351 --> 13:49.516
You're cancelling again?

13:49.541 --> 13:50.740
I am so sorry, Rosemary.

13:50.765 --> 13:52.673
I just need to get some
grading done, and...

13:52.698 --> 13:53.820
try to get some sleep.

13:53.845 --> 13:54.696
No, no.

13:54.721 --> 13:58.749
I understand; you need your
rest and relax-that's it!

13:58.986 --> 14:00.952
Laura, can you babysit tomorrow night?

14:00.977 --> 14:01.942
Sure.

14:01.967 --> 14:02.672
Why?

14:02.697 --> 14:06.020
We are going to have
a ladies only night.

14:06.045 --> 14:10.360
One night of relaxation
and rejuvenation.

14:10.553 --> 14:12.219
Oh! You deserve it.

14:12.244 --> 14:13.438
We both do!

14:13.463 --> 14:14.805
Count me in!

14:14.830 --> 14:17.098
Oh, oh!

14:17.949 --> 14:19.651
[CHUCKLES]

14:27.058 --> 14:28.621
Hey Bill.

14:29.141 --> 14:33.053
You seem a little shaken

14:33.265 --> 14:37.043
and I'm guessing it's more
than the tremor this morning.

14:38.741 --> 14:40.713
I've been offered a judgeship.

14:41.354 --> 14:44.524
[LAUGHS]

14:45.417 --> 14:47.082
That's funny.

14:48.165 --> 14:50.105
Oh, you're serious.

14:51.863 --> 14:53.383
Well how, why?

14:53.408 --> 14:55.714
Well, it started with
me roughing up a judge.

14:56.695 --> 14:59.126
That hardly seems like a qualification.

14:59.151 --> 15:01.022
It has to do with law, and order,

15:01.047 --> 15:03.215
and integrity, and toughness.

15:03.803 --> 15:06.891
Well, wow, that's
great, congratulations.

15:06.916 --> 15:08.921
Well, I haven't decided if
I'm going to take it yet.

15:09.457 --> 15:11.039
Because?

15:11.064 --> 15:12.994
I don't know if I want it.

15:13.386 --> 15:15.565
Besides, I hate lawyers.

15:17.139 --> 15:19.854
Right. Yes, that would be a problem.

15:22.048 --> 15:24.009
- [HUMMING MERRILY]
- ♪

15:24.034 --> 15:25.700
What song is that?

15:25.725 --> 15:27.706
"You have stolen my heart

15:27.731 --> 15:29.347
"Now please don't go away

15:29.372 --> 15:31.531
"As we sang love's old sweet song

15:31.556 --> 15:32.415
"On Moonlight Bay."

15:32.440 --> 15:34.866
Ah, that's a beautiful song.

15:34.891 --> 15:35.969
For some reason,

15:35.994 --> 15:38.622
it keeps playing in my head these days.

15:39.791 --> 15:41.124
Woah, woah, woah.

15:41.159 --> 15:42.471
Oh, no!

15:42.693 --> 15:44.068
What now?

15:44.266 --> 15:45.861
We'll have to go the long way around,

15:45.886 --> 15:47.649
we won't make it back tonight.

15:47.983 --> 15:50.309
Well, we didn't bring
anything to camp with.

15:51.150 --> 15:52.866
We'll make do.

16:00.910 --> 16:02.243
What is it?

16:02.880 --> 16:04.983
Well, take a look.

16:06.315 --> 16:09.176
That is 15 feet from where you dug.

16:09.314 --> 16:10.451
It's dry.

16:10.476 --> 16:12.185
Yeah, completely.

16:12.588 --> 16:14.438
I'm thinking between the tremor we had,

16:14.463 --> 16:16.035
and your well digging,

16:16.060 --> 16:19.259
a small pocket of surface
oil was released.

16:19.284 --> 16:20.328
But!

16:20.353 --> 16:22.586
I did find some indication of cap rock.

16:22.905 --> 16:24.263
What does that mean?

16:24.289 --> 16:26.519
Well, it means there might
be a larger oil reservoir

16:26.544 --> 16:27.910
further down.

16:27.935 --> 16:29.015
Might?

16:29.040 --> 16:31.135
[SIGHS]

16:33.593 --> 16:35.893
This is shale.

16:40.201 --> 16:42.502
That suggests to me your
chances are decent.

16:42.661 --> 16:44.454
How decent?

16:45.298 --> 16:47.465
Well, without further
testing, it's hard to say.

16:47.495 --> 16:50.360
Give the kids your best
guess estimate, Glen.

16:50.957 --> 16:54.959
Best guess, I'd say you have
about a 40 percent chance.

16:54.984 --> 16:56.174
40 percent!

16:56.199 --> 16:58.100
Yeah, that... that's something.

16:58.125 --> 17:01.422
Yeah, you might have to dig another
3 to 6,000 feet to find out.

17:01.841 --> 17:03.203
Uh, thousand?

17:03.228 --> 17:04.429
Yeah.

17:04.454 --> 17:05.839
How do I do that?

17:05.864 --> 17:08.125
With a lot of men and rotary drills.

17:08.150 --> 17:09.483
And it will cost you.

17:09.508 --> 17:10.740
How much?

17:10.765 --> 17:12.146
Depends on how deep you gotta dig;

17:12.171 --> 17:13.936
could be several thousand dollars.

17:13.962 --> 17:16.419
Why is everything thousands?

17:16.700 --> 17:18.640
It's just the way it is with oil.

17:27.869 --> 17:35.775
<i>[FIRE CRACKLES]</i>

17:36.192 --> 17:38.443
Are you sure you'll be all
right without a sleeping bag?

17:38.468 --> 17:40.141
Yeah, I'm fine.

17:40.166 --> 17:44.003
I used to go camping all the
time with my three brothers.

17:44.446 --> 17:46.679
So, I'm used to the elements.

17:46.704 --> 17:48.070
[LAUGHS]

17:48.095 --> 17:49.820
We never went camping.

17:50.289 --> 17:52.481
My mom and dad were not keen on it.

17:52.506 --> 17:53.771
Oh.

17:53.869 --> 17:55.436
Are they still alive?

17:55.520 --> 17:57.966
My mom passed away a long time ago.

17:58.844 --> 18:00.487
My dad's alive, though.

18:00.521 --> 18:02.837
At least you still have one parent.

18:04.432 --> 18:06.109
Not exactly.

18:09.037 --> 18:11.467
My dad and I haven't spoken in years.

18:13.281 --> 18:14.844
I'm sorry.

18:15.842 --> 18:18.188
Do you mind if I ask why?

18:21.442 --> 18:28.412
Well, it starts with my
mom, who was a nurse.

18:29.543 --> 18:34.970
She died of typhoid fever, which
she caught from a patient.

18:35.753 --> 18:39.869
And when dad found out I
wanted to be a nurse too,

18:41.389 --> 18:43.057
he got really upset.

18:43.937 --> 18:45.878
I can see why.

18:47.913 --> 18:49.934
I understand his concern.

18:51.754 --> 18:56.394
But sometimes, it's about the
words you use to express it.

18:58.182 --> 19:03.791
My dad, he called me a fool.

19:04.695 --> 19:07.170
And I was tired of his disapproval.

19:09.038 --> 19:11.045
We haven't spoken since.

19:13.935 --> 19:16.293
You, Miss Carter, are a lot of things,

19:16.318 --> 19:18.949
but you are not a fool.

19:33.418 --> 19:35.816
Class may I have your
attention, please?

19:36.122 --> 19:37.741
Thank you.

19:38.301 --> 19:41.159
I would like to introduce
you to our newest student,

19:41.184 --> 19:42.145
Allie.

19:42.170 --> 19:43.240
Please welcome her.

19:43.265 --> 19:45.850
(CLASS) Hi Allie.

19:46.797 --> 19:49.424
Allie, you may take a
seat next to Robert.

19:51.558 --> 19:53.305
<i>Now, then.</i>

19:53.673 --> 19:58.317
Cleopatra, known as
the Queen of Egypt...

19:58.342 --> 19:59.254
Pick a card.

19:59.279 --> 20:00.950
<i>You might be surprised to learn,</i>

20:00.975 --> 20:04.017
<i>was actually Greek, hmm?</i>

20:04.185 --> 20:06.038
Bet you I can guess your card.

20:06.063 --> 20:10.302
<i>Cleopatra was only 18 years old
when she first ruled Egypt.</i>

20:10.327 --> 20:12.519
<i>Which is a great responsibility.</i>

20:12.544 --> 20:15.299
So it's a good thing she
was very intelligent.

20:15.468 --> 20:18.867
<i>Not only did she love
math and philosophy,</i>

20:18.892 --> 20:22.318
<i>but she also spoke seven
different languages.</i>

20:22.690 --> 20:24.035
<i>Impressive, right?</i>

20:24.060 --> 20:25.106
<i>[LAUGHS]</i>

20:25.131 --> 20:28.396
So Henry... What can I do for you?

20:29.085 --> 20:32.376
You mind if I ask you a
somewhat personal question?

20:33.263 --> 20:34.795
Probably.

20:34.820 --> 20:36.116
But give it a shot.

20:36.955 --> 20:40.341
What is it about poker that
you find so appealing?

20:40.941 --> 20:42.469
The stakes.

20:42.998 --> 20:44.465
The excitement.

20:44.490 --> 20:45.775
The payout.

20:45.800 --> 20:48.070
Everything has a calculated risk,

20:48.095 --> 20:50.268
I mean, you're not luckier
than the next man.

20:50.369 --> 20:52.056
You just know the game.

20:52.618 --> 20:54.975
What I know is that this
conversation has a point.

20:55.000 --> 20:57.726
And I just haven't figured
out what it is yet.

20:58.899 --> 21:03.085
You gamble in poker, but
there's another game.

21:03.636 --> 21:05.246
The bigger risk,

21:05.271 --> 21:09.188
but the potential for
a much bigger reward.

21:09.452 --> 21:13.284
I know how to play that
game, if you're interested.

21:26.667 --> 21:28.481
<i>[ALL] Wow!</i>

21:28.506 --> 21:29.948
Do it again!

21:29.973 --> 21:31.768
Thank you.

21:33.870 --> 21:35.568
What's going on here?

21:38.023 --> 21:40.189
Everyone inside, now.

21:41.565 --> 21:43.021
Not you.

21:43.819 --> 21:45.185
Now, hand it over.

21:45.210 --> 21:46.410
What?

21:46.627 --> 21:48.092
The bag.

21:57.636 --> 21:59.064
Where did you get all of this?

21:59.089 --> 22:00.480
It was just a card trick.

22:00.505 --> 22:01.845
I won it fair and square.

22:01.870 --> 22:03.417
The trick part leads me to believe

22:03.442 --> 22:05.612
there was nothing "fair" about it.

22:05.692 --> 22:07.243
And I have to say, I'm
a little dismayed

22:07.268 --> 22:09.547
that your uncle would
teach you such a thing.

22:09.572 --> 22:10.704
Uncle Nathan?

22:10.729 --> 22:12.263
Pfft. Hardly.

22:12.288 --> 22:13.954
All he knows how to play is old maid.

22:13.979 --> 22:15.512
Then, who taught it to you?

22:15.537 --> 22:17.170
I'd rather not say.

22:18.234 --> 22:20.328
<i>You don't have to say.</i>

22:22.599 --> 22:24.176
I know who it was.

22:24.946 --> 22:26.373
Sorry, gents.

22:26.398 --> 22:28.867
Seems to be a lucky day for the house.

22:30.176 --> 22:32.203
I may have spoken too soon.

22:32.672 --> 22:34.168
We need to talk.

22:35.858 --> 22:37.342
Deal me out.

22:41.261 --> 22:43.338
What were you thinking, teaching
a young girl to gamble?

22:43.362 --> 22:45.715
She's only 10 years old.
Do you have any idea...

22:45.740 --> 22:47.748
Woah, woah, I'm assuming
we're talking about Allie.

22:47.773 --> 22:50.121
Unless you opened up a
gambling school for minors.

22:50.146 --> 22:51.190
Let's just calm down.

22:51.224 --> 22:52.565
Mr. Bouchard, do not
tell me to calm down,

22:52.590 --> 22:54.056
I have every right to be upset.

22:54.151 --> 22:55.687
You taught a young girl how to gamble.

22:55.712 --> 22:57.209
I did not teach Allie to gamble.

22:57.234 --> 22:58.598
I taught her a card trick.

22:58.623 --> 22:59.924
Two very different things.

22:59.949 --> 23:01.768
Frankly, I was doing your job.

23:01.946 --> 23:03.478
Excuse me?

23:03.503 --> 23:05.446
I was just trying to get Allie
interested in going to school.

23:05.471 --> 23:07.507
By teaching her a card trick.

23:07.844 --> 23:10.209
Allie was nervous about
meeting the other kids,

23:10.234 --> 23:11.334
making friends.

23:11.359 --> 23:13.193
I told her it would break the ice.

23:14.869 --> 23:16.935
Well, it certainly did that.

23:17.846 --> 23:19.844
How much did she win?

23:21.120 --> 23:23.631
Mr. Bouchard, that is beside the point.

23:24.311 --> 23:26.831
I appreciate you trying to help.

23:27.018 --> 23:28.751
But if there ever is a next time,

23:28.920 --> 23:31.083
please just bring Allie back to school.

23:44.861 --> 23:46.986
Mr. Bouchard may have been misguided,

23:47.011 --> 23:49.809
but I believe his heart
was in the right place.

23:50.144 --> 23:51.644
[SIGHS]

23:51.669 --> 23:54.980
Has Allie had trouble fitting
in at any of her other schools?

23:56.415 --> 23:57.747
[SIGHS]

23:57.772 --> 24:00.159
She hasn't been around long
enough for that to matter.

24:00.222 --> 24:02.549
Which I think could very
well be the problem.

24:02.788 --> 24:04.748
Allie isn't making an effort
because she doesn't think

24:04.773 --> 24:07.136
she'll be here long
enough for it to matter.

24:08.168 --> 24:09.449
[SIGHS]

24:09.474 --> 24:11.755
You know how the Mounties work.

24:13.810 --> 24:16.827
I also know that
children need stability.

24:18.359 --> 24:20.165
We're fine, thank you.

24:20.190 --> 24:23.108
So, what I suggest is
that we call Allie in,

24:23.133 --> 24:25.005
and let her know what our
expectations of her are

24:25.030 --> 24:26.692
in the classroom.

24:29.728 --> 24:31.192
All right?

24:34.568 --> 24:35.965
Okay.

24:45.077 --> 24:47.347
Allie, could you come inside please?

24:50.945 --> 24:52.492
[DOOR CLOSES]

24:52.517 --> 24:55.018
[FOOTSTEPS]

24:58.335 --> 25:01.782
Allie, do you understand why it
was wrong to take money and food

25:01.807 --> 25:03.117
from the other children?

25:03.142 --> 25:04.975
It's not like I forced them to play.

25:05.000 --> 25:06.599
That's not the issue.

25:06.624 --> 25:08.736
You deliberately tricked
the other children.

25:08.875 --> 25:10.947
Allie, I raised you better than that.

25:12.190 --> 25:14.054
Tomorrow, you're going
to return everything,

25:14.079 --> 25:15.288
and you're going to apologize.

25:15.313 --> 25:16.813
I don't have it anymore.

25:16.859 --> 25:18.898
Mrs. Thornton took my bag.

25:24.606 --> 25:26.171
Are we understood?

25:27.248 --> 25:28.680
Yes, Sir.

25:34.173 --> 25:39.577
Allie, are you anxious
about making friends

25:39.602 --> 25:41.311
with the other children?

25:45.775 --> 25:48.067
Have you ever read Emmerson?

25:49.249 --> 25:51.181
He's one of my favourite poets.

25:51.206 --> 25:55.711
And he has some incredibly
wise quotes including,

25:56.287 --> 25:59.861
"the only way to have a
friend is to be one."

26:01.199 --> 26:04.265
But, the only friend I've
ever had is Uncle Nathan.

26:04.290 --> 26:06.147
And he has to like me.

26:06.427 --> 26:08.228
[CHUCKLES]

26:08.335 --> 26:11.087
Oh, Allie, I'm sure it seems scary.

26:11.447 --> 26:13.881
But if you just be
yourself, I guarantee you,

26:13.906 --> 26:15.872
you'll make a ton of friends.

26:16.207 --> 26:18.859
I happen to know that Robert and
Opal already like you a lot.

26:18.884 --> 26:19.783
Really?

26:19.808 --> 26:20.673
Mm-hmm.

26:20.698 --> 26:22.170
Definitely.

26:22.620 --> 26:25.160
You just have to give the
other kids a chance.

26:26.458 --> 26:28.272
Can you do that for me?

26:29.226 --> 26:30.608
I guess.

26:41.248 --> 26:42.547
Jessie.

26:42.572 --> 26:43.937
Can I talk to you for a moment?

26:43.962 --> 26:45.628
Yeah, of course.

26:45.955 --> 26:47.853
I'd like to buy your land.

26:49.195 --> 26:50.294
Why?

26:50.319 --> 26:52.163
Well, I'd like to dig and look for oil.

26:52.188 --> 26:54.364
Well, what makes you think I
don't wanna do the same thing?

26:54.389 --> 26:57.296
Well, there's a difference
between wanting and doing.

26:57.472 --> 26:59.887
We both know that you don't
have the money to dig.

27:00.193 --> 27:03.192
So I'm willing to offer you
twice what you paid for it,

27:03.217 --> 27:05.019
$1,000.

27:05.743 --> 27:07.469
$1,500.

27:07.823 --> 27:09.522
$1,200.

27:09.547 --> 27:11.493
That's my final offer.

27:11.896 --> 27:13.824
[SIGHS]

27:15.428 --> 27:16.942
I'll have to talk to Clara first.

27:16.967 --> 27:18.299
Sure.

27:18.788 --> 27:19.913
Give me until tomorrow?

27:19.938 --> 27:21.475
Yeah, yeah.

27:21.500 --> 27:23.592
- Take care.
- Yeah.

27:38.433 --> 27:40.202
Where's little Jack?

27:41.373 --> 27:42.572
There he is!

27:42.597 --> 27:45.531
[BABY GIGGLES]

27:45.673 --> 27:46.839
Where's little Jack?

27:46.864 --> 27:48.297
He was just here!

27:48.322 --> 27:49.717
There you are!

27:50.131 --> 27:54.219
I have everything all ready
for our "ladies only" night.

27:54.244 --> 27:57.968
By tomorrow, you will feel
completely rejuvenated.

27:58.113 --> 27:59.381
[DISAPPOINTED] No!

27:59.406 --> 28:00.505
I'm so sorry.

28:00.530 --> 28:02.256
Laura's dad needed her tonight.

28:02.281 --> 28:04.420
Their cow is expecting
a calf any minute.

28:04.445 --> 28:05.146
Really?

28:05.171 --> 28:06.036
Really.

28:06.061 --> 28:08.270
Laura felt awful; so did I.

28:08.295 --> 28:10.337
But I told her not to worry about it.

28:10.499 --> 28:12.598
We'll do it another time.

28:12.885 --> 28:14.451
Sure we will.

28:16.040 --> 28:18.058
[SIGHS]

28:18.083 --> 28:20.551
[BABY GIGGLES]

28:20.826 --> 28:22.900
<i>Hello, little man.</i>

28:30.961 --> 28:36.114
[METAL CLANKING]

28:41.370 --> 28:43.083
Is everything okay?

28:43.777 --> 28:46.247
I hope I didn't get too
personal last night.

28:46.428 --> 28:48.227
It wasn't too much, too soon?

28:48.252 --> 28:49.919
Not for me.

28:50.901 --> 28:52.643
<i>Oh.</i>

29:03.691 --> 29:05.044
Hey sweetheart.

29:06.437 --> 29:07.870
Hi.

29:10.010 --> 29:11.609
What's got you down?

29:11.753 --> 29:13.050
Disappointment.

29:13.075 --> 29:14.308
Dismay.

29:14.333 --> 29:16.851
Dashed expectations.

29:18.149 --> 29:20.837
Well, that does sound bleak.

29:21.098 --> 29:23.464
Is there anything I can do to help?

29:25.781 --> 29:27.820
Maybe there is.

29:33.367 --> 29:34.810
Now, Lee, are you sure?

29:34.835 --> 29:36.138
Elizabeth, I got this.

29:36.163 --> 29:36.996
Go!

29:37.021 --> 29:38.354
Have some fun.

29:38.379 --> 29:40.128
Well, he's teething, so he
might be a little fussy.

29:40.153 --> 29:42.715
It's no problem-we're going
to have a good time, right?

29:42.740 --> 29:43.958
Yes, we are.

29:43.983 --> 29:45.202
Yes, we are.

29:45.227 --> 29:47.911
[LAUGHS]

29:48.192 --> 29:49.821
Oh, all right.

29:50.389 --> 29:51.888
[KISSING SOUNDS]

29:52.056 --> 29:53.730
<i>Bye bye!</i>

29:53.755 --> 29:55.984
[WHISPERS] Bye bye.

29:57.699 --> 29:59.334
Oh come on, it's literally next door.

29:59.359 --> 30:01.259
It's not like I don't
know where to find you.

30:01.284 --> 30:02.521
Promise me if there's
anything you need,

30:02.546 --> 30:03.378
you'll come right over?

30:03.403 --> 30:05.035
I promise. Now, go!

30:05.060 --> 30:06.517
You're crampin' our guy time.

30:06.542 --> 30:07.649
Right?

30:07.674 --> 30:10.484
"Bye Momma, you're
cramping our guy time!"

30:10.574 --> 30:12.627
Momma's crampin' our guy time.

30:12.952 --> 30:14.245
So, what should we do?

30:14.270 --> 30:15.059
Here we are.

30:15.084 --> 30:16.265
You wanna play peekaboo?

30:16.290 --> 30:17.389
Whoop. Where'd I go?

30:17.414 --> 30:18.738
Whoop. There I am!

30:18.763 --> 30:20.340
Whoop, I'm gone. Whoop, there I am!

30:20.365 --> 30:21.245
[BABY GIGGLES]

30:21.270 --> 30:23.059
That's fun, right?

30:24.519 --> 30:26.933
I had my doubts about Constable
Grant's parenting skills,

30:26.958 --> 30:28.691
but he has proven me wrong.

30:28.716 --> 30:32.478
Well, it can't be easy raising
such a spirited little girl,

30:32.503 --> 30:33.668
all on your own.

30:33.693 --> 30:35.317
I'm sure it isn't.

30:35.715 --> 30:37.976
Did you ever find out what
happened to Allie's parents?

30:38.001 --> 30:41.632
No, they are pretty private people.

30:44.606 --> 30:46.106
I have to say,

30:46.131 --> 30:49.122
I'm just so happy to
have you here right now.

30:49.147 --> 30:51.164
Thank you so much for
doing this, Rosemary.

30:51.189 --> 30:53.289
Hmm-mm. Well, let's celebrate.

30:53.473 --> 30:54.679
There you are.

30:54.704 --> 30:56.586
- Cheers.
- Cheers!

30:59.112 --> 31:01.068
We are going to have
some fruit and cookies

31:01.093 --> 31:02.387
and finger sandwiches-

31:02.412 --> 31:05.306
Oh, I almost forgot to put
the muffins in the oven.

31:05.331 --> 31:07.648
Oh, that's really not...

31:08.227 --> 31:10.074
necessary.

31:11.872 --> 31:13.960
[KNOCKING AT DOOR]

31:13.985 --> 31:15.062
Ohhh...

31:16.170 --> 31:18.150
[WHISPERS] Who is that at the door?
Huh?

31:18.175 --> 31:19.715
Who is that at the door?

31:19.740 --> 31:21.719
Let's go see.

31:25.540 --> 31:26.629
Hey, Bill.

31:26.654 --> 31:28.321
- Hey.
- What are you doing here?

31:28.346 --> 31:31.354
Well, I heard Elizabeth had
some words with Bouchard,

31:31.379 --> 31:33.464
because he was teaching
some kid to gamble.

31:33.489 --> 31:35.361
Hmm, well, that's news to me.

31:35.386 --> 31:37.498
Uh, she's next door
with Rosemary, though.

31:37.523 --> 31:38.776
But I wouldn't go over there.

31:38.801 --> 31:39.965
Oh, why not?

31:39.990 --> 31:41.656
It's a woman's soiree, right?

31:41.681 --> 31:42.981
No men allowed.

31:43.006 --> 31:44.013
But do come in, please.

31:44.038 --> 31:45.667
- Oh, thanks.
- Yeah.

31:47.620 --> 31:48.919
You know, you're doing that wrong.

31:48.944 --> 31:50.346
No, no, we're fine.

31:50.371 --> 31:52.480
Oh, no, your vest won't be
once he spits up on it.

31:52.505 --> 31:53.892
Here. Give him to me.

31:53.917 --> 31:54.994
Mmm-hmmm.

31:55.019 --> 31:56.318
There you go.

31:56.343 --> 31:58.076
Grab that towel, will ya?

31:58.101 --> 31:59.715
Sure.

32:01.142 --> 32:06.106
Okay, yeah. Oh, I can feel it in there.

32:06.131 --> 32:07.481
- Thank you.
- You're welcome.

32:07.506 --> 32:09.484
Here we go, here we go, ready?

32:14.702 --> 32:16.201
[BELCHES]

32:16.226 --> 32:17.720
See? It just takes practice.

32:17.745 --> 32:19.185
HmmMmm.

32:19.210 --> 32:21.236
Come here you, oh!

32:21.261 --> 32:24.591
Oh, my goodness, did
you have a big burp.

32:24.616 --> 32:26.647
Yes, I think you did!

32:26.672 --> 32:28.568
Why wouldn't you do it for me?

32:28.593 --> 32:30.738
Oh, there we go.

32:30.763 --> 32:32.902
Now, let's cover you up,
'cause it's a little chilly.

32:32.927 --> 32:34.591
He's gonna get too hot.

32:34.616 --> 32:36.557
No, no, no, there's a draft.

32:36.582 --> 32:37.749
I don't feel it.

32:37.774 --> 32:39.466
Don't you have some
Sheriff-y stuff to do?

32:39.491 --> 32:42.159
Don't you have some...
tree to cut down?

32:42.449 --> 32:44.160
[SIGHS]

32:44.838 --> 32:46.511
Yeah.

32:47.866 --> 32:49.144
<i>[LAUGHING]</i>

32:49.169 --> 32:50.688
<i>Talk about embarrassing.</i>

32:50.713 --> 32:51.757
Do you remember the time...

32:51.782 --> 32:53.270
I thought I was being
taken to San Francisco

32:53.295 --> 32:54.937
to star in a new musical

32:54.962 --> 32:56.256
and I was actually being kidnapped.

32:56.281 --> 32:57.331
[LAUGHS]

32:57.356 --> 32:59.012
You really were a damsel in distress.

32:59.037 --> 33:02.387
Let me tell you it's more fun
to play one than be one.

33:02.595 --> 33:05.270
I was running away from those
men and then who do I see

33:05.295 --> 33:07.426
in his red surge coming towards me.

33:07.451 --> 33:08.350
Jack.

33:08.375 --> 33:10.764
Hmm-mm. Always the hero.

33:10.938 --> 33:12.735
He sure was.

33:12.918 --> 33:15.481
But I know you saved him
in more ways than one.

33:15.877 --> 33:17.898
I remember when he first came to town

33:17.923 --> 33:20.212
he hated it here so much.

33:20.237 --> 33:21.854
Gee, I wonder what changed his mind.

33:21.879 --> 33:23.368
Oh.

33:23.393 --> 33:25.105
People find true love in Hope Valley.

33:25.130 --> 33:26.661
It's true. You and Jack.

33:26.686 --> 33:28.134
You and Lee.

33:28.159 --> 33:29.429
Clara and Jesse.

33:29.454 --> 33:30.560
Yes.

33:30.585 --> 33:31.794
Faith and Carson.

33:31.819 --> 33:33.302
Yes. Wait, what, no.

33:33.327 --> 33:37.465
Uh... how do you...
You know about that?

33:37.693 --> 33:39.215
Well, doesn't everyone?

33:39.240 --> 33:41.542
No, no, they're not supposed to know.

33:41.567 --> 33:43.220
How did you find out?

33:43.384 --> 33:46.476
Carson and Faith are terrible liars.

33:46.501 --> 33:51.243
[LAUGHTER]

33:51.839 --> 33:53.406
<i>Well, here they come now.</i>

33:53.431 --> 33:57.353
Faith, I know being estranged
from your father bothers you.

33:57.775 --> 34:00.333
Have you thought about
reaching out to him?

34:01.152 --> 34:03.029
Hundreds of times.

34:03.054 --> 34:04.720
And what stops you?

34:07.111 --> 34:08.978
Fear of rejection?

34:11.246 --> 34:14.141
Anybody would be crazy to reject you.

34:18.580 --> 34:20.123
Um...

34:21.848 --> 34:24.033
Do you think they know about us?

34:44.885 --> 34:47.248
If they weren't before, they are now.

34:50.101 --> 34:51.952
Come on.

34:55.080 --> 34:56.478
Well...

34:59.006 --> 35:00.384
[SIGHS]

35:00.409 --> 35:04.326
So, $1,200 is a lot of money, Jessie.

35:04.351 --> 35:05.788
I know.

35:05.951 --> 35:09.737
I could pay off my debt, and
we'd have some left over.

35:09.762 --> 35:11.105
To build our house.

35:11.130 --> 35:12.800
I really like the sound of that.

35:13.200 --> 35:14.775
Me too.

35:15.391 --> 35:16.998
Have we decided?

35:26.595 --> 35:28.664
[GIGGLES]

35:28.689 --> 35:30.956
[BABY CRIES]

35:31.816 --> 35:33.043
Baby's hungry.

35:33.068 --> 35:34.500
I fed him an hour ago.

35:34.525 --> 35:36.120
Maybe he needs his diaper changed.

35:36.145 --> 35:38.196
I changed him just before you got here.

35:38.221 --> 35:39.324
Didn't you say he was teething?

35:39.349 --> 35:40.669
Oh, right, yes!

35:40.694 --> 35:42.059
There's a cloth in the
ice bucket right there

35:42.084 --> 35:43.420
in the corner.

35:43.787 --> 35:45.049
Thank you.

35:46.638 --> 35:47.815
Hey.

35:47.840 --> 35:48.939
He stopped.

35:48.964 --> 35:50.130
He just wanted you to go away.

35:50.155 --> 35:51.065
[LAUGHS]

35:51.090 --> 35:53.424
You just wanted Bill to
go away, didn't you?

35:53.678 --> 35:54.860
Yes!

35:54.885 --> 35:56.755
It's just a joke.

35:56.780 --> 35:58.152
I mean, it wasn't that funny.

35:58.177 --> 35:59.988
Starting to look more
like Jack, isn't he?

36:00.013 --> 36:02.108
Yeah, yeah he really is.

36:02.289 --> 36:03.608
Think he'll be a Mountie?

36:03.633 --> 36:04.487
Ha.

36:04.512 --> 36:06.930
Not if Elizabeth has
anything to do with it.

36:07.204 --> 36:09.050
Well, for what it's worth,

36:10.182 --> 36:12.368
I think you'd make a fine judge, Bill.

36:12.848 --> 36:14.274
Well, thanks, Lee.

36:14.299 --> 36:15.775
Appreciate that.

36:15.941 --> 36:17.640
And just so you know,

36:17.699 --> 36:19.968
I think you'd make a great dad someday.

36:20.867 --> 36:22.299
Yeah?

36:22.454 --> 36:23.754
Thank you.

36:31.536 --> 36:34.242
This has been so relaxing.

36:34.549 --> 36:37.424
All work and no play
is no good for you.

36:37.449 --> 36:38.849
Or you.

36:38.874 --> 36:40.060
Every time I see you

36:40.085 --> 36:41.873
it seems like you've taken
on some new project.

36:41.898 --> 36:44.735
You are the busiest
person I know, Rosemary.

36:44.813 --> 36:46.588
Well, it's different for me.

36:46.613 --> 36:50.077
You have a job and a
child, that's a lot.

36:51.406 --> 36:54.271
Every day I count my blessings that
I have little Jack is in my life.

36:54.296 --> 36:58.457
But I have to admit, it's
been pretty wonderful

36:58.482 --> 37:00.415
just being me for an evening.

37:02.685 --> 37:06.787
Yes, even the most devoted
mother needs to have a break

37:06.812 --> 37:08.520
once in a while.

37:10.408 --> 37:12.002
Are you alright?

37:13.107 --> 37:15.156
Yes, yes, I'm fine.

37:16.328 --> 37:17.513
You sure?

37:17.538 --> 37:18.736
[OVEN DINGS]

37:19.312 --> 37:21.467
Oh... the muffins are ready.

37:28.827 --> 37:32.496
♪

37:43.400 --> 37:45.032
I always got a game.

37:50.070 --> 37:51.847
Excuse me gentlemen.

37:54.630 --> 37:56.063
I'm sorry.

37:56.088 --> 37:58.483
I heard about what
happened with your niece.

37:59.328 --> 38:01.508
No more teaching kids
card tricks, okay?

38:01.837 --> 38:03.509
As you wish.

38:04.332 --> 38:06.477
What's your story, Bouchard?

38:06.924 --> 38:08.690
Why are you such an expert at cheating?

38:08.715 --> 38:10.305
I'm not.

38:10.538 --> 38:13.373
In fact, I've only
cheated once in my life.

38:15.248 --> 38:16.820
This is a great town.

38:16.845 --> 38:20.265
Good people, fine opportunities.

38:20.908 --> 38:22.688
What's your point?

38:22.904 --> 38:25.039
You don't seem like a good fit here.

38:25.064 --> 38:26.716
[CHUCKLES]

38:27.141 --> 38:29.288
That's kind of the story of my life.

38:29.994 --> 38:31.890
But I'm not going anywhere.

38:48.556 --> 38:54.019
[SNORING]

39:06.678 --> 39:08.374
You ate half my muffin!

39:08.399 --> 39:10.098
It wasn't very good.

39:16.490 --> 39:17.898
My apple.

39:17.923 --> 39:20.220
Now that was tasty!

39:21.669 --> 39:23.368
<i>Opal!</i>

39:24.596 --> 39:25.862
Here's your candy.

39:25.931 --> 39:26.963
You didn't like it?

39:26.998 --> 39:28.498
I didn't taste it.

39:28.533 --> 39:30.199
Here, I hope you like it.

39:30.268 --> 39:32.237
Black liquorice is my favourite.

39:32.366 --> 39:34.266
I don't like liquorice.

39:46.041 --> 39:48.976
Here's the $200 for
the drilling rights.

39:49.449 --> 39:51.950
As stated in the contract,
if we strike oil,

39:51.975 --> 39:54.490
you'll receive 30 percent
of the crude that comes up

39:54.515 --> 39:56.118
from your rig.

39:57.706 --> 39:59.872
Nice doing business with you, Mr.
Gowen.

39:59.897 --> 40:01.648
Pleasure, Miss Hayford.

40:16.234 --> 40:18.856
That's the eighth option today.

40:18.954 --> 40:21.360
You seem to be throwing a
lot of my money around.

40:21.480 --> 40:23.714
Welcome to high stakes gambling.

40:23.739 --> 40:26.038
I just hope you know what you're doing.

40:26.063 --> 40:28.292
[LAUGHS SMUGLY]

